WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.920
I'm going to teach you three levels of rain&nbsp;
animation in After Effects. We are going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:03.920 --> 00:00:09.280
increase the difficulty level as we climb the&nbsp;
evolutionary tree. Not only by using more advanced&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:18.000
techniques, but by using basic techniques in&nbsp;
smarter and smarter ways. [Music] So, in ape mode,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:22.560
we'll go over to our effects and presets panel&nbsp;
and type in rain to see if anything comes up.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.560 --> 00:00:27.680
And here we have CC rainfall. That sounds just&nbsp;
like what we want. Let's add that to a black&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:33.200
solid. And that's certainly rain, but we can make&nbsp;
it look much better. Let's bump up the opacity to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:38.240
see it a little more. And the size, too. Now,&nbsp;
it also reflects the background by default,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.240 --> 00:00:43.040
which makes it a bit harder to see. So, let's&nbsp;
turn that influence all the way down. And let's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:48.560
also put a lovely gradient behind our rain and&nbsp;
change the rains blending mode from normal to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:53.760
screen to see behind it. Let's turn the drops&nbsp;
quite a bit down as well. And this effect has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.760 --> 00:01:01.360
two really amazing tricks up its sleeve. The first&nbsp;
is speed. The speed controls how fast or how slow&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:07.040
the raindrops fall and also their length as well.&nbsp;
The faster they are, the more the raindrops smear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.040 --> 00:01:12.240
and we get these bigger lines for the raindrops.&nbsp;
When it's really slow, they are just circles.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:12.240 --> 00:01:16.800
And we can animate this for a nice speed ramp.&nbsp;
So, let's key frame this starting really high.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:23.360
Let's go to 15,000. There we go. Very fast. Key&nbsp;
frame that there. And then about 2 seconds later,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:23.360 --> 00:01:30.640
let's really lower it to maybe 150. Let's add a&nbsp;
bit of easing. And look at that. And I'm also not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.640 --> 00:01:35.760
too keen on the rain all going in very slightly&nbsp;
different directions. So, let's turn the spread&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:41.040
from six down to zero. So, now they're all going&nbsp;
straight downwards. And at the really slow speed,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.040 --> 00:01:46.080
we can see the second great thing about this&nbsp;
effect, and that is that there is depth. Depth&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:46.080 --> 00:01:52.160
in 3D space. These drops have parallax. The drops&nbsp;
that are closer are a little larger and they move&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:57.040
faster, which is harder to see in the chaos, but&nbsp;
you really do notice it once they start to slow&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:57.040 --> 00:02:02.240
down. And we can adjust that with the scene depth.&nbsp;
Let's increase it a little bit more. Let's not go&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:02.240 --> 00:02:08.640
crazy. And in our extras, we can enhance that even&nbsp;
more with the ground level percentage. So, if we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:08.640 --> 00:02:13.280
adjust this, we can see some of the raindrops are&nbsp;
disappearing. And this is where they would hit the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:13.280 --> 00:02:18.320
ground and disappear. So, we get even extra depth&nbsp;
there. And we can create a simple splash animation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.320 --> 00:02:23.120
for each of these raindrops. So I'll grab my&nbsp;
ellipse tool, create an ellipse, and animate it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:23.120 --> 00:02:29.040
increasing its size and fading out. And even at&nbsp;
the a level, we know to animate an ellipse's size&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:29.040 --> 00:02:33.920
and not its scale. That way, we can keep it stroke&nbsp;
width consistent. Now, we can trim that layer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:38.000
place it where one of the raindrops disappears,&nbsp;
and we've got a convincing little splash. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.720
we can pre-ompose that splash and drag that&nbsp;
wherever the drops disappear. There we get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:49.200
a lovely peaceful rainy scene with a speed ramp&nbsp;
and lots of depth. Not bad for an ape. I will be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:49.200 --> 00:02:54.480
honest though, timing all of those splashes&nbsp;
took ages. So, I only did half the screen,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:54.480 --> 00:03:00.800
which you can only really get away with if&nbsp;
your animation is from the POV of a pirate.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:09.680
But you know what they say, you pay peanuts,&nbsp;
you get monkeys. I know monkeys aren't apes.

00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:15.280
For the elevated ape, we're after a more cool and&nbsp;
stylized rain effect. And much like our ancestors,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:15.280 --> 00:03:19.920
we are leaving the trees and going to take&nbsp;
our attention to the ground. How the raindrops&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.920 --> 00:03:25.760
interact with it, but this time in a much smarter&nbsp;
way. We're evolving. I was inspired by this image,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.760 --> 00:03:30.560
thinking that those two colors with the rings&nbsp;
overlapping into the alternate color looked&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:30.560 --> 00:03:35.440
really cool. The first way I tried to do this&nbsp;
was with a single ripple comp with three circles&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.440 --> 00:03:39.520
expanding then fading away. They each have&nbsp;
a drop shadow, so there's a black and white&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:39.520 --> 00:03:44.720
version of each circle. I put a bunch of those&nbsp;
comps in a line and then overy background. Then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.720 --> 00:03:50.080
I added just a couple of effects, a threshold to&nbsp;
restrict it to either black or white, and then a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:55.600
tint to recolor it. Now, this isn't too bad. The&nbsp;
core idea is there, but it would need a fair bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.600 --> 00:04:01.200
more attention to get it looking the way I wanted.&nbsp;
And I found an easier way. I discovered the effect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:01.200 --> 00:04:06.480
CC drizzle. And this is what it looks like by&nbsp;
default. It has all those ripples randomly and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.480 --> 00:04:11.120
has that interaction when they overlap. Exactly&nbsp;
what we want. Now, let's start from scratch in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:11.120 --> 00:04:16.000
a new comp. We'll create a new solid with Ctrl +&nbsp;
Y. We'll make it gray, but we'll make the height&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.720
about three times larger than our comp. And I'll&nbsp;
explain why soon. Add the drizzles to that. Uh,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:25.600
we'll increase the drip rate a little bit more&nbsp;
to eight to fill up our larger solid. Open up the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:30.960
shading. And we'll increase the diffuse lighting&nbsp;
to the max so we can see more of the detail of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.960 --> 00:04:36.160
the ripples. And we will need this a bit darker.&nbsp;
So let's take down the ambient light to maybe 15&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:41.280
or so. Now to make these look like we are looking&nbsp;
at them from a lower angle and not directly above,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.280 --> 00:04:46.640
what we can do is unlink the scale of this layer&nbsp;
and then lower the vertical scale squashing it.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:51.120
This is why we started with that comp being&nbsp;
much taller so we can scale it down without a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.120 --> 00:04:56.640
running out of layer. Then on a new adjustment&nbsp;
layer which we are going to rename to effects&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.640 --> 00:05:00.960
because we always label our layers. Let's add the&nbsp;
threshold effect. And this starts really shaping&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.960 --> 00:05:06.720
it into that final look we want that will just be&nbsp;
two colors. Now I do want a clear separation of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:06.720 --> 00:05:11.840
light and shadow in here. And we can do that by on&nbsp;
our drizzle layer opening up the light properties&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:11.840 --> 00:05:16.800
and changing it from distant light which is kind&nbsp;
of far away and lighting everything evenly to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.800 --> 00:05:21.120
point light which lights only in a specific&nbsp;
area. And let's move that light position to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:26.640
the very center of our comp. And we can lower the&nbsp;
light height as well so it shines on a smaller and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:31.600
smaller area. And the light is still catching a&nbsp;
lot of these ripples far away from the light. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:36.400
if we do lower the ripple height, that should get&nbsp;
rid of a lot of those. I don't want a few, but not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:36.400 --> 00:05:41.280
too many. There. Now we're getting very close.&nbsp;
And we can also adjust the light intensity as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:46.640
well to grow and shrink how much of that area is&nbsp;
illuminated. And just tweak all of these values,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:46.640 --> 00:05:52.800
the ambient light, the diffuse as well, just to&nbsp;
hone in on the the look we want. I like it around&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.800 --> 00:05:57.120
this level. Now, to make it a bit more moody,&nbsp;
let's add some more effects. a lot of my very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.120 --> 00:06:02.400
frequently used favorites. Let's add a tint&nbsp;
to recolor it. We'll map the black to a very,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:02.400 --> 00:06:08.880
very dark gray and the white to a pure blue. We'll&nbsp;
add a bit of gausian blur to soften it. And we'll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:13.600
treat ourselves to a deep glow. You do have to&nbsp;
be subtle though. Homminids are more than capable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:18.960
to use tools very skillfully. So, do remember if&nbsp;
you're walking upright, keep the glow light. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.960 --> 00:06:24.000
if you don't have deep glow, a few regular glows&nbsp;
are just fine. We'll add a transform effect with a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.480
wiggle on the position property to add that tiny&nbsp;
shake for some gate weave. I talked a lot about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.480 --> 00:06:33.760
that in my last video. Good old posterized time&nbsp;
to set the frame rate to 12 frames per second. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:33.760 --> 00:06:38.960
then some grain with some noise HLS auto. And for&nbsp;
some extra atmosphere, let's add some raindrops&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.960 --> 00:06:43.680
falling that might catch this light. So I'll grab&nbsp;
the pen tool and just draw a line coming straight&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:48.880
down. We'll animate its shape path. We only need&nbsp;
to do that over about three key frames. I'll say&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:53.360
I'll make them all hold key frames so there's&nbsp;
no blending in between them and we get something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.360 --> 00:06:58.320
like that. And let's put that under the adjustment&nbsp;
layer. And we'll set it blending mode from normal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:58.320 --> 00:07:03.200
to difference. This way it'll show the inverse of&nbsp;
what's underneath it. So when it's on top of black&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:08.080
it'll become blue. And when it's on top of blue&nbsp;
it'll become black. Well, it will all be black and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.080 --> 00:07:12.480
white, but the the tint will be turning it into&nbsp;
into blue or black. Now let's move the anchor&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:12.480 --> 00:07:17.760
point to the very bottom of that layer. hit R on&nbsp;
our keyboard and adjust the rotation of that drop&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:22.400
to have it coming in from any angle we like. And&nbsp;
we can get really smart with this. Let's duplicate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:22.400 --> 00:07:27.040
this layer. Let me just nudge that over for a&nbsp;
second. And on the rotation of this raindrop, I'm&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.040 --> 00:07:31.520
simply going to get the pick whip and select the&nbsp;
rotation of our first one. So now they are linked.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.520 --> 00:07:36.720
And every duplicate I make, the rotation can be&nbsp;
adjusted from that original one. So the direction&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:42.000
will be consistent across every raindrop we make.&nbsp;
Now that's evolution, baby. Let's spread them out&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:50.080
across the scene there. I'm not trying to match&nbsp;
the ripples, just match the vibe. [Music] Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:50.080 --> 00:07:55.120
that's something I could lo-fi study and relax&nbsp;
to. And if we turn that effects layer on and off,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.120 --> 00:08:00.400
we can see just how much those effects are shaping&nbsp;
the result. The threshold effect in particular,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:05.680
I am absolutely threshold pills at the moment.&nbsp;
It's such a great effect for pulling interesting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:05.680 --> 00:08:11.520
2D stylized looks out of 3D looking effects that&nbsp;
just uh don't quite get there on their own. No&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:11.520 --> 00:08:17.760
disrespect to CC Drizzle, all my Drizzlers out&nbsp;
there. And before we get to the very highest&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:22.880
third evolutionary level of rain, let's split&nbsp;
the evolutionary line where apes now have full&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:30.240
control over the planet and take the core of this&nbsp;
effect to push it even further. So, I thought this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:30.240 --> 00:08:35.680
effect could make a really cool movie title for&nbsp;
maybe an 80s horror film. So I slapped some text&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:35.680 --> 00:08:40.240
over the top. Change it blending mode again to&nbsp;
difference. And when I tried a boulder weight,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:40.240 --> 00:08:44.960
I loved how the ripples kind of came in and out&nbsp;
of the text. The difference inverting them right&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:44.960 --> 00:08:49.680
next to one another made it look a bit kind&nbsp;
of checkerboardy and not natural at all. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:54.000
I knew I could do a much better job with just&nbsp;
a few changes. So instead of laying the text&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:58.320
over the ripples, let's use the shape of the&nbsp;
ripples themselves to warp the letters using&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:03.920
a displacement map. So let's change their blending&nbsp;
mode back to normal. And we want to add the effect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:09.120
displacement map to that text layer. Now for our&nbsp;
displacement map layer, we want to use our drizzle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:09.120 --> 00:09:14.720
layer and make sure we use the effects and mask as&nbsp;
the source because those ripples are being made by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:19.440
that drizzle effect. And now we can also hide&nbsp;
that drizzle layer. We'll need a a background.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:24.560
I'll quickly make a black background with a solid.&nbsp;
And we can also hide those raindrops for now. Can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:29.280
barely see it now, but if we increase the amount&nbsp;
of horizontal displacement, we can start to see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:34.320
the effect working. the darker values in that&nbsp;
drizzle layer warping our text layer to the right.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:39.040
It's technically using the red values for the&nbsp;
displacement here. But because our drizzle layer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:39.040 --> 00:09:44.720
is grayscale, the red, the green, the blue give&nbsp;
the same result. True equality. And now it looks&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:44.720 --> 00:09:49.520
like our text is either on or underneath some&nbsp;
water that is being disturbed by those ripples,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:54.720
which is exactly what we want. There is just two&nbsp;
things we need to correct. First is that the pin&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:54.720 --> 00:09:59.440
light, which is making it brighter in the middle,&nbsp;
is kind of warping the center. So on our drizzle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:59.440 --> 00:10:04.160
layer, let's change that light from point light&nbsp;
to distant light. We can hide it again. Put our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:04.160 --> 00:10:08.640
effects back on. That sorts that out. And now our&nbsp;
ripples are back to being perfect circles as seen&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:08.640 --> 00:10:12.720
from above, which is okay. That works fine if you&nbsp;
want that. But I want these to appear at an angle.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:12.720 --> 00:10:17.760
Now this is happening because our displacement&nbsp;
map effect is not taking into account that we've&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:23.040
squashed the scale on that uh drizzle layer. So we&nbsp;
can easily fix that just by pre-mping this drizzle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:23.040 --> 00:10:27.280
layer and making sure we move all attributes&nbsp;
to the new composition. And now our ripples&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:31.600
are nice and squashed because that displacement&nbsp;
map is looking at a comp that has squashed layers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:36.080
inside it. Now we can tweak the ripples to get&nbsp;
the effect we want there. Now it's looking really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:39.920
like it's under some water. Another thing you&nbsp;
might have noticed is that the displacement map&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:39.920 --> 00:10:44.400
is pushing our layer out of the center a bit down&nbsp;
and to the right. Now we could just nudge it back&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:44.400 --> 00:10:48.880
into the center and eyeball it to get it in the&nbsp;
middle, but that wouldn't be very Dr. Zaius of us,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:52.880
now would it? To keep this and any other layers we&nbsp;
might want to use in the center, all we need to do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:52.880 --> 00:10:57.760
is go into that drizzle pre-MP and make this&nbsp;
background a perfect 50% gray. At the moment,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:57.760 --> 00:11:02.240
it is a little bit darker. So, it is displacing&nbsp;
everything to the right. But if it's a completely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:02.240 --> 00:11:07.200
neutral 50% gray, just the ripples will affect&nbsp;
the text, not the darkness of the background. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:11.040
I find the easiest way to do this is to&nbsp;
just create a shape layer, make sure its&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:17.440
color is exactly 50% gray, and then adjust the&nbsp;
ambient shading on that drizzle to match. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:22.000
as homminids, we have traded our night vision for&nbsp;
incredible color perception. So, this should be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:25.760
no trouble at all. And now, we don't need the&nbsp;
shape layer anymore. So, we can just fling that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:25.760 --> 00:11:30.880
off onto looking bystanders. And back in our main&nbsp;
comp, our text is centered beautifully. We can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:30.880 --> 00:11:35.440
bring back those raindrops. Maybe move them into&nbsp;
some new positions. I do want to make sure they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:35.440 --> 00:11:43.680
are on top of our text as well. And then think&nbsp;
of the perfect title for an 80s slasher movie.

