grayscale because we can color those with effects&nbsp;
later. For the ripples, I figured I could create a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:01.360 --> 00:14:05.520
single one and then duplicate that for all the&nbsp;
others. So, we'll start with that one first.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:05.520 --> 00:14:10.080
This is what the final result of that looks like.&nbsp;
And this was a bit of a repetitive process with a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:10.080 --> 00:14:14.880
fair bit of experimentation to get this look.&nbsp;
So, instead of going through it step by step,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:17.920
which would take much too long and be very&nbsp;
boring, I'm going to walk you through what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:17.920 --> 00:14:21.760
each one of these layers does and what they're&nbsp;
adding to this effect. Again, everything is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:25.600
included in the project files. So, this is in&nbsp;
a separate comp. Now, the background is gray,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:25.600 --> 00:14:29.760
but that is just so we can see this clearly. If&nbsp;
we turn the transparency on, we can see that it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:29.760 --> 00:14:33.520
is just these ripples and their shading. That's&nbsp;
so that when we start stacking the ripples so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:33.520 --> 00:14:37.360
we can see the ones underneath. So let's remove&nbsp;
everything back to the first layer. Pretty much&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:37.360 --> 00:14:42.400
the only animation in this whole thing which is a&nbsp;
single ellipse increasing its size. And I've got a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:42.400 --> 00:14:47.520
few key frames on it stroke width as well. Just&nbsp;
expanding and easing in pretty slowly. I'll put&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:52.240
the background back on. And I have two effects on&nbsp;
that. I have a gausian blur just for some initial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:52.240 --> 00:14:56.480
softening. And then I have a directional blur&nbsp;
as well which softens it more horizontally. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:56.480 --> 00:15:00.960
that's to create a bit more of a tapering effect&nbsp;
as this kind of rolls off the edges into the sort&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:00.960 --> 00:15:05.120
of the flat plane of the water or at least give&nbsp;
that illusion. Then I created a duplicate version&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:05.120 --> 00:15:09.680
of that layer and lowered it down. So this sits&nbsp;
underneath and is even more blurred to get more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:09.680 --> 00:15:13.520
of that tapered look. So it's a bit sharper at the&nbsp;
top and softer at the bottom. And that is the main&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:13.520 --> 00:15:17.840
shape we're working with. Then for a highlight,&nbsp;
I added another duplicate. This time colored it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:17.840 --> 00:15:23.680
white and really shrank down the stroke width. And&nbsp;
for this one, I added two masks. So now only this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:23.680 --> 00:15:29.120
top left section and this bottom right section of&nbsp;
that highlight are visible. Those masks are also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:29.120 --> 00:15:33.920
feathered as well, so we don't have a harsh line.&nbsp;
This comp is all about keeping everything soft.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:33.920 --> 00:15:38.560
Then some more blurs back on top of those. And&nbsp;
then I did the same thing for the shading. This is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:38.560 --> 00:15:43.600
just a dark layer this time lower down feathered&nbsp;
masks as well in those same areas. And then blurs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:43.600 --> 00:15:48.960
back on top. This I did set to preserve underlying&nbsp;
transparency. So it is only affecting the pixels&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:48.960 --> 00:15:53.280
underneath. We turn transparency back on here.&nbsp;
That is off. and it is sort of creating more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:53.280 --> 00:15:57.920
pixels. But if we turn this on, it is restricted&nbsp;
to just the existing pixels underneath. Everything&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:57.920 --> 00:16:03.680
else is transparent is preserved. Then I did two&nbsp;
more versions of that layer. Each one moving it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:03.680 --> 00:16:09.120
slightly down and making it a little bit softer.&nbsp;
Then I put an adjustment layer over everything and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:09.120 --> 00:16:14.960
animated a directional blur and a gausian blur to&nbsp;
blur it out even more as it gets wider so it gets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:14.960 --> 00:16:19.600
softer and softer flattening into the water. Now,&nbsp;
the ultimate way to soften it was to actually add&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:19.600 --> 00:16:24.320
the gradient background from our main comp over&nbsp;
the top of everything and then have that slowly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:24.320 --> 00:16:28.720
fade in. So, by the end of this comp, it will&nbsp;
look exactly like the background. And then a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:28.720 --> 00:16:33.600
preserved underlying transparency on that so that&nbsp;
again it only affects our ring and not the rest of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:33.600 --> 00:16:38.320
the comp. And then the last thing to make it even&nbsp;
softer was just to add a few more duplicates of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:43.360
layers and slightly darker grays which did expand&nbsp;
out a little bit from the ring to kind of make it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:43.360 --> 00:16:47.680
look like they are maybe casting shadows and just&nbsp;
make it super super soft. And here's how that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:47.680 --> 00:16:53.360
looks back in our main comp. It gets softer and&nbsp;
then fades out nicely. Then it was time to animate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:53.360 --> 00:16:58.000
the raindrop. First just falling down. And of&nbsp;
course we want it to enter the water. So I added&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:02.960
a mask which is just a shape layer with a slight&nbsp;
blur on it and use that as a mat for our raindrop&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:08.320
layer. I animated the position of our raindrop&nbsp;
to jump up and down I think about three times and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:08.320 --> 00:17:13.440
each time it jumps up and down it gets smaller.&nbsp;
Just animating its scale so it loses some mass&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:13.440 --> 00:17:17.200
while it is underneath the water. And then on&nbsp;
the last one it kind of lands on the surface&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:17.200 --> 00:17:21.920
of the water above the mat. And then I actually&nbsp;
parented it to a null. Then animated that null&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:21.920 --> 00:17:26.080
scale to kind of squash and stretch as if it was&nbsp;
just bouncing on the surface before it finally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:26.080 --> 00:17:30.800
fades in under the water. I created duplicates&nbsp;
of the ripples and lined them up for whenever the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:35.680
circle entered or exited the water. Now, having&nbsp;
the ripple layer on top means that it covers the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:35.680 --> 00:17:40.800
ripple layer underneath, which I did not want. So,&nbsp;
to get around that, what I did was create a mask,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:40.800 --> 00:17:45.840
which cuts that layer in half, feathered that&nbsp;
mask a little bit, then duplicated that layer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:45.840 --> 00:17:50.480
inverted that mask, so now these two layers have&nbsp;
either side of that ripple, and drag the ripple&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:50.480 --> 00:17:55.440
on the bottom underneath that previous layer in&nbsp;
the layer stack. So, now it looks stacked in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:55.440 --> 00:18:00.320
uh the right order. I did that a whole bunch&nbsp;
of times, adding extra ripples in between the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:00.320 --> 00:18:05.520
bounces and just timing those to make sure they&nbsp;
all aligned up nicely. That created a few extra&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:05.520 --> 00:18:10.240
layers, but nothing too out of hand. I also&nbsp;
added a shadow to the raindrop, which is just an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:10.240 --> 00:18:14.560
ellipse with some blurs on it. And for the final&nbsp;
colors and effects, I added a gausian blur,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:14.560 --> 00:18:18.640
and that just unifies that very sharp circle&nbsp;
with everything underneath it. Some grainy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:18.640 --> 00:18:24.400
noise with noise HLS auto. And then I colored it&nbsp;
with CC toner. Now, another extra effect I tried&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:24.400 --> 00:18:29.040
and you might be after is a slight strobing to&nbsp;
the whole animation. So, this is created with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:29.040 --> 00:18:32.960
another adjustment on a layer over the top of&nbsp;
everything. I have a curves effect on it and I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:32.960 --> 00:18:38.480
have its opacity animated to go from 100 to zero&nbsp;
back to 100 with a looping expression on that. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:38.480 --> 00:18:43.600
this curves effect is really subtle. We don't want&nbsp;
to have to put a warning on our animation. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:43.600 --> 00:18:48.160
this kind of mimics a light source flickering when&nbsp;
filmed with an extreme slow motion camera. I'm not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:48.160 --> 00:18:53.200
sure if it's necessary for this animation, but it&nbsp;
is a really useful strong visual cue that you're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:53.200 --> 00:18:57.040
watching something in slow motion. So, a good and&nbsp;
really simple trick to keep up your sleep if you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:57.040 --> 00:19:03.520
ever want to lean into that. Most of these rain&nbsp;
techniques and skills we've covered have so many&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:03.520 --> 00:19:09.520
applications beyond rain. Layers of feathered&nbsp;
masks and blurs can create softer gradients and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:09.520 --> 00:19:15.280
satisfying shading to anything. Displacement maps&nbsp;
can warp any layer based on the values of another.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:24.240
threshold can turn gray messes into bold designs&nbsp;
and CC rainfall can make rain fall. We have gone&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:24.240 --> 00:19:30.320
from knuckle dragging to neurons bragging and made&nbsp;
a troop of friends along the way. Please let me&nbsp;&nbsp;

